courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students should be able to:
• Gain a good understanding of contemporary SLA theories;
• Critique a range of issues related to SLA with reference to teaching and learning;
• Show a good understanding of applications of SLA theories to research and teaching;
• Demonstrate the ability to conceptualize empirical research guided by SLA theories.
(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
demonstrate a solid understanding of key theoretical concepts of second language assessment;
construct, critique, adapt and score language tests; conduct test item analysis; and report and interpret test results;
develop a strong grasp of summative and formative assessment, assessment of, for and as learning, and alternative assessment, with specific reference to how assessment can be used to support classroom instruction; and
reflect critically on conventional assessment approaches in the light of best practices in language assessment.
(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
Discuss and evaluate different research methods in TESOL;
Formulate research questions relating to issues in TESOL and suggest appropriate research designs to investigate these issues;
Define, exemplify and discuss key concepts and terms including external/internal reliability and validity, construct operationalization, and variables;
Critique a range of data collection procedures and methods, including introspection, diary studies, questionnaires, interviews, and discoursal analysis; and
Demonstrate the ability to analyze sample qualitative and quantitative data.
(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
conceive, design and carry to completion an independent research study that explores a significant issue in TESOL;
conduct a thorough review of literature pertinent to the research study;
demonstrate skills in the collection and critical analysis of data;
write up the research study into a dissertation of 8,000 to 10,000 words; and
make an original contribution to the field of study through the independent research study.
(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)
